<p><b>Orthostatic hypotension</b> (also known as <b>postural hypotension</b><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>, and, colloquially, as <b>head rush</b> or a <b>dizzy spell</b>) is a form of <a href="/wiki/Hypotension" title="Hypotension">hypotension</a> in which a person's <a href="/wiki/Blood_pressure" title="Blood pressure">blood pressure</a> suddenly falls when the person stands up. The decrease is typically greater than 20/10 <a href="/wiki/Mm_Hg" title="Mm Hg" class="mw-redirect">mm Hg</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-pmid18091397_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pmid18091397-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> and may be most pronounced after resting.</p>
<p>The incidence increases with age.<sup id="cite_ref-pmid17976425_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pmid17976425-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
